What is Data Science?

Career paths

Data science is a fast-growing field. The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) expects data science jobs to grow 36% between 2023 and 2033, much faster than other occupations. Here are some possible career paths after completing our data science course online:
Data scientist
Professional data scientists write programs to generate corporate insights from structured and unstructured data.
median salary for Data scientist
$108,000
Sources: Bureau of Labor Statistics
Data engineer
Data engineers build systems that collect and organize data for subsequent analysis.
median salary for Data engineer
$133,000
Sources: Glassdoor.com
Machine learning/AI engineer
Machine learning/AI engineers build predictive analytics models for organizations.
median salary for Machine learning/AI engineer
$167,000
Sources: Glassdoor.com
Data analyst
Data analysts gather, process, and perform statistical analysis on business data.
median salary for Data analyst
$110,000
Sources: Glassdoor.com
Data architects
Data architects plan and design an organization's data management infrastructure. They work closely with data engineers to implement their vision.
median salary for Data architects
$188,000
Sources: Glassdoor.com
More than 2,300 entry-level job openings in the United States, with ~10,000 openings at all levels
Data science is a field that combines statistics, advanced analytics, and programming to predict outcomes from raw, often unstructured, data. Data Scientists build predictive models, train AI, and create algorithms that find patterns in the noise of the world’s data.

Download PDF
Our immersive data scientist training will teach you to analyze and manipulate datasets and train Machine Learning models. You’ll learn how to use Python, Excel, and SQL databases to retrieve, analyze, manipulate, and build predictive models from datasets.
This section of our full data science course provides the foundation for career advancement. Python is a popular programming language widely used in data applications, machine learning/AI, and building digital tools. In this module, you'll learn how to use Python for data analysis and to build predictive models.
Data Science has many facets. One of the most widely used is Machine Learning (ML), which involves teaching computers to find the best algorithms to perform specific tasks and creating models to make predictions and inferences about the real world.

Machine Learning builds on everything you've covered so far—stats, Python, and software engineering—to enable you to create intelligent systems. You'll cover supervised learning (including regression and classification models) and machine learning and apply your knowledge to real-world business projects.
Data science is always advancing—new tech is constantly being developed, and an amazing array of possibilities are opening up in the field. It's more than you can learn in a lifetime, but we'll make sure to take you through a curated selection of the most interesting data science advancements.

This module covers Time Series (handling data with a time dimension), Unsupervised Learning, Natural Language Processing, Neural Networks applied to Computer Vision, and more!
Creating a finished product. This part of the program is entirely practical, resulting in a real data science project.
